    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider the number <m>\alpha = \sqrt{3}+\sqrt{5}</m> and the field <m>\Q(\alpha)</m>, a simple extension of <m>\Q</m>.
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Prove that <m>\alpha</m> is an algebraic number.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Is <m>\Q(\alpha)</m> an extension field of <m>\Q(\sqrt{3})</m>?  Is it an extension field of <m>\Q(\sqrt{5})</m>?  Explain.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                If we take <m>\Q(\sqrt{3})</m> and adjoin <m>\sqrt{5}</m>, do we get a bigger field?  We can write <m>\Q(\sqrt{3})(\sqrt{5})</m> as <m>\Q(\sqrt{3},\sqrt{5})</m>. 
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Find the minimal polynomials for <m>\sqrt{3}</m> over <m>\Q</m> and of <m>\alpha = \sqrt{3}+\sqrt{5}</m> of <m>\Q(\sqrt{3})</m>.  How do the degrees of these relate to the degree of the polynomial you found for <m>\alpha</m> in part (a)?
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <hint>
        <p>
          For (b), first decide whether <m>\Q(\alpha)</m> contains the element <m>\sqrt{15}</m>.  If it does, note that it must also contain <m>\sqrt{15}(\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{5}) - 3(\sqrt{3}+\sqrt{5})</m>.  Why is this helpful?
        </p>
      </hint>
    </exercise>
  </exercises>